# tooling-wave-b-pr-fix-mesh-playbook — History

## v1.1.0 (2026-05-31)

**Changed by:** Wave-B swarm cleanup follow-up — verifying/finishing the swarm's
own auto-fix run (PRs across HomericIntelligence/* that the Wave-B executor logged
as "pass" but were actually still red).
**Verification:** verified-ci — the cleanup fixes were pushed and the targeted
checks observed turning green in live CI.

### What changed

- Added a leading "Trust nothing the swarm logged" rule: Wave-B auto-fix executors
  run a headless print-mode verification window that times out (`TIMEOUT_PENDING`)
  before slow AchaeanFleet CI finishes, so the swarm records optimistic
  `#NN pass` results. Always re-query live with `gh pr checks` + `gh run view
  --log-failed`.
- Added the `gh pr checkout` shallow-clone trap: in a shallow clone `gh pr checkout`
  silently leaves HEAD on `main`, so commits/pushes go to `main` and are rejected by
  branch protection. Fix: fetch + checkout the explicit `headRefName` by name.
- Added the "fix the REAL file the live log names, not the headline file" rule — the
  same rule can fail in a different file than the analysis named (e.g. MD013 in
  CONTRIBUTING.md after fixing it in branch-protection.md).
- Added the MD060-IS-autofixable nuance alongside the existing MD013-is-NOT note.
- Added "confirm the PR isn't already MERGED before treating a missing head ref as a
  failure" rule.
- Added the clang-format version-mismatch demote-don't-thrash lesson.
- Added 5 new Failed Attempts rows from this session.
- Bumped version 1.0.0 → 1.1.0 (minor: new findings + new failed attempts, core
  recommendation unchanged).

### Why

v1.0.0 already said "gh pr checks lies; the check-runs API does not," but it did not
warn that the SWARM'S OWN run log lies even harder (it never waits for CI at all —
its verification window times out and it records optimistic passes). It also lacked
the `gh pr checkout`-stays-on-main trap, the fix-the-actually-failing-file rule, the
already-merged guard, and the clang-format version-mismatch demote rule. These were
the concrete failures that wasted time finishing a Wave-B run, so they belong in the
playbook.

